WEBVTT

00:05.130 --> 00:06.381
<i>Previously on</i> The Affair...

00:06.465 --> 00:09.092
Here she is.

00:09.176 --> 00:10.886
The one that got away.

00:10.969 --> 00:13.055
There's not a‐a day goes by
where I don't

00:13.138 --> 00:13.931
<i>regret what happened in Paris.</i>

00:14.014 --> 00:16.058
‐Don't fucking touch me!
‐[slaps]

00:16.141 --> 00:19.394
This wedding is gonna be
a fucking disaster.

00:19.478 --> 00:20.354
What is it?

00:20.437 --> 00:21.730
I cheated on Colin.

00:21.813 --> 00:24.608
<i>And I have to tell him, right?</i>

00:24.691 --> 00:25.984
He could give you a gallery.

00:26.068 --> 00:28.153
Do you remember teaching a class

00:28.237 --> 00:30.364
with a student named Audrey?

00:30.447 --> 00:31.907
[Noah]
Unfortunately, all that Audrey

00:31.990 --> 00:34.076
has revealed here today
is how shockingly

00:34.159 --> 00:36.578
unoriginal her inner life
actually is.

00:36.662 --> 00:37.913
Helen Solloway?

00:37.996 --> 00:41.124
Eden Ellery.
I‐I was Noah's publicist.

00:41.208 --> 00:42.918
I think they were
sleeping together.

00:43.001 --> 00:44.294
‐[Sasha] <i>When?</i>
‐[Helen] <i>On his book tour.</i>

00:44.378 --> 00:44.920
[Petra]
<i>'Cause Ellery mentioned</i>

00:45.003 --> 00:47.381
<i>a party in the Hamptons.</i>

00:47.464 --> 00:49.299
You didn't pressure her
into sex that night?

00:49.383 --> 00:50.425
Absolutely not.

00:50.509 --> 00:52.427
[Petra]
<i>Are you sure?</i>

00:52.511 --> 00:54.096
[Noah]
<i>Yeah, I'm sure.</i>

00:54.179 --> 00:55.597
<i>I‐I remember the night</i>
<i>very well.</i>

00:55.681 --> 00:57.641
Dad, what the fuck?!

00:57.724 --> 01:00.602
[screams]
Dad, get out!

01:09.194 --> 01:12.322
<i>♪ I was screaming</i>
<i>into the canyon ♪</i>

01:12.406 --> 01:14.825
<i>♪ At the moment of my death ♪</i>

01:14.908 --> 01:17.995
<i>♪ The echo I created ♪</i>

01:18.078 --> 01:21.206
<i>♪ Outlasted my last breath ♪</i>

01:21.290 --> 01:25.168
<i>♪ My voice it made</i>
<i>an avalanche ♪</i>

01:25.252 --> 01:28.422
<i>♪ And buried a man</i>
<i>I never knew ♪</i>

01:28.505 --> 01:31.550
<i>♪ And when he died,</i>
<i>his widowed bride ♪</i>

01:31.633 --> 01:34.136
<i>♪ Met your daddy</i>
<i>and they made you ♪</i>

01:34.219 --> 01:35.304
<i>♪ I have only one thing to do ♪</i>

01:35.387 --> 01:38.640
<i>♪ And that's be the wave</i>
<i>that I am, and then ♪</i>

01:38.724 --> 01:40.976
<i>♪ Sink back into the ocean ♪</i>

01:41.059 --> 01:42.936
<i>♪ I have only one thing to do ♪</i>

01:43.020 --> 01:45.147
<i>♪ And that's be the wave</i>
<i>that I am, and then ♪</i>

01:45.230 --> 01:47.566
<i>♪ Sink back into the ocean ♪</i>

01:47.649 --> 01:49.776
<i>♪ I have only one thing to do ♪</i>

01:49.860 --> 01:52.070
<i>♪ And that's be the wave</i>
<i>that I am, and then ♪</i>

01:52.154 --> 01:55.115
<i>♪ Sink back into the ocean,</i>
<i>sink back into the ocean ♪</i>

01:55.198 --> 01:56.033
<i>♪ Sink back into the o... ♪</i>

01:56.116 --> 01:58.493
<i>♪ Sink back into the ocean ♪</i>

01:58.577 --> 02:00.120
<i>♪ Sink back into the o... ♪</i>

02:00.203 --> 02:01.872
<i>♪ Sink back into the ocean ♪</i>

02:01.955 --> 02:04.458
<i>♪ Sink back</i>
<i>into the ocean ♪</i>

02:19.222 --> 02:22.017
Um, we were already
in mediation

02:22.100 --> 02:24.519
by the time the book came out,
so I‐I don't know.

02:24.603 --> 02:26.438
You'll have to ask him that.

02:27.814 --> 02:30.192
Well, it was mediation.

02:30.275 --> 02:33.195
It doesn't get friendlier
than that, right?

02:34.821 --> 02:37.741
Joint custody.

02:40.452 --> 02:43.038
Okay, look, I...
it's great that you're writing

02:43.121 --> 02:45.582
about Noah's book,
but I really don't

02:45.666 --> 02:47.459
have anything to say
about our marriage.

02:47.542 --> 02:50.253
Um, it‐it ended
a long time ago.

02:53.799 --> 02:55.342
Yeah. No‐no comment.

02:57.469 --> 02:58.053
[phone clicks]

02:58.136 --> 03:02.140
<i>♪ quiet, somber music ♪</i>

03:09.106 --> 03:11.191
<i>♪♪♪</i>

03:15.654 --> 03:18.031
Hey.

03:18.907 --> 03:20.200
That took a while.

03:20.283 --> 03:22.577
Yeah.

03:22.661 --> 03:24.830
How'd you like Petra?

03:25.664 --> 03:27.666
Did you know
she was gonna call me?

03:27.749 --> 03:28.667
No.

03:28.750 --> 03:30.961
What did she want?

03:31.044 --> 03:32.295
Sh...
What'd you do with my wine?

03:32.379 --> 03:35.841
Oh, I poured it out.
I thought you were done.

03:35.924 --> 03:38.260
I hate when people do that.

03:41.638 --> 03:44.141
It was pretty annoying,
actually,

03:44.224 --> 03:47.102
because she said
she was just fact‐checking,

03:47.185 --> 03:50.689
and then... she just started
asking me all these questions

03:50.772 --> 03:52.190
about our divorce.

03:52.274 --> 03:53.650
What did you say?

03:54.109 --> 03:56.236
"No comment."

03:57.154 --> 03:58.780
Thanks for doing that.

04:02.576 --> 04:03.326
What is the article
about, anyway?

04:03.410 --> 04:05.036
I thought it was
about your new book.

04:05.120 --> 04:07.497
I have no fucking idea.

04:07.581 --> 04:11.042
The publisher pitched it to me
as a redemption story.

04:11.126 --> 04:15.630
You know, my new book and
the movie and how I'd made good.

04:15.714 --> 04:18.383
Now, suddenly, Petra's digging
around looking for skeletons

04:18.467 --> 04:20.135
like it's some
tabloid piece.

04:20.218 --> 04:22.512
I mean, honestly,
I'm starting to regret

04:22.596 --> 04:24.473
I agreed to be interviewed
in the first place.

04:26.892 --> 04:28.810
Is she finding any skeletons?

04:33.482 --> 04:35.150
Well, nothing about
weddings in Montauk,

04:35.233 --> 04:36.693
if that's what you mean.

04:36.777 --> 04:38.653
And she never will.

04:42.824 --> 04:44.534
[sighs softly]

04:44.618 --> 04:47.579
She asked a lot of questions
about your dating history.

04:47.662 --> 04:50.248
‐That's what I mean.
‐But why would she care?

04:50.332 --> 04:51.374
I don't know.

04:51.458 --> 04:54.127
Is it... I mean, it's not...

04:54.211 --> 04:56.505
turning into some kind
of #MeToo story, is it?

04:56.588 --> 04:58.006
No.

05:00.425 --> 05:03.303
And even if it is,
Gottlief says he can kill it.

05:03.386 --> 05:04.429
You've been talking to Gottlief?

05:04.513 --> 05:06.807
Well, I just wanted
to make sure I'm prepared.

05:06.890 --> 05:08.475
You just said there was
nothing to worry about.

05:08.558 --> 05:09.935
There isn't, but, you know,

05:10.018 --> 05:11.686
this day and age,
things have a tendency

05:11.770 --> 05:13.188
‐to spiral out of control.
‐Okay, well, why don't you

05:13.271 --> 05:14.773
just tell me exactly
what's going on.

05:14.856 --> 05:16.441
‐Nothing. Like I said.
‐Because, if this is

05:16.525 --> 05:18.401
gonna affect me or the kids,
I have to know.

05:18.485 --> 05:20.028
I mean, I have to know.

05:20.111 --> 05:22.030
We've just...
we've been through too much.

05:22.113 --> 05:24.199
I'm handling it,
okay, Helen?

05:24.282 --> 05:27.327
Gottlief, my agent,
my publisher,

05:27.410 --> 05:29.412
they've all dealt with
these things a thousand times.

05:29.496 --> 05:30.914
This is what they do now.

05:30.997 --> 05:33.416
It's gonna be fine. Okay?

05:33.500 --> 05:35.544
<i>♪ quiet, atmospheric music ♪</i>

05:35.627 --> 05:37.462
<i>♪♪♪</i>

05:41.967 --> 05:44.261
Okay.

05:46.638 --> 05:48.557
I, uh... I have a walkthrough
of a house tomorrow

05:48.640 --> 05:51.518
with my new boss,
so I need to get some sleep.

05:51.601 --> 05:53.186
Can you lock the door
when you go?

05:54.187 --> 05:55.355
Okay.

05:57.440 --> 05:58.525
<i>♪♪♪</i>

06:25.302 --> 06:27.387
<i>♪♪♪</i>

06:42.485 --> 06:44.988
[sighs]

06:52.078 --> 06:53.997
[food sizzling]

06:54.080 --> 06:55.290
[phone chimes]

06:55.373 --> 06:57.292
[phone clicking]

06:57.375 --> 06:58.335
Hey, what's this?

06:58.418 --> 06:59.794
‐[Stacey] I know.
‐Hey.

06:59.878 --> 07:00.629
[Stacey]
We came down, and he had

07:00.712 --> 07:03.506
the whole mise en place
raring to go.

07:03.590 --> 07:05.967
Okay, <i>Top Chef.</i>
Noah, what's going on?

07:06.051 --> 07:07.385
Yeah, I was heading out,
but, uh,

07:07.469 --> 07:08.887
the winds were pretty intense,

07:08.970 --> 07:10.013
and I'm exhausted.

07:10.096 --> 07:11.348
I'm on... still
on Eastern time.

07:11.431 --> 07:12.599
I didn't want to bother you.

07:12.682 --> 07:13.808
You said you needed some rest.

07:13.892 --> 07:15.393
Can I get some coffee?

07:16.561 --> 07:18.063
Do you drink coffee now?

07:18.146 --> 07:19.314
‐[Helen] No.
‐[Trevor] Mm‐hmm.

07:19.397 --> 07:20.315
[Noah and Helen]
No.

07:20.398 --> 07:23.318
‐[Eddie coos]
‐[Sierra] Hey.

07:23.401 --> 07:25.320
Hey. Uh, how'd you sleep?

07:25.403 --> 07:26.821
Too well, actually.
Woke up in a panic

07:26.905 --> 07:29.324
'cause it was light out and he
was still asleep. Thank you.

07:29.407 --> 07:32.118
Um, are you sure
it's okay if we stay

07:32.202 --> 07:33.411
a couple more days?

07:33.495 --> 07:35.830
I feel like,
if I can keep this up,

07:35.914 --> 07:39.834
like, this normal feeling,
maybe I can find a lawyer

07:39.918 --> 07:41.503
‐to help me with CPS.
‐[phone chimes]

07:41.586 --> 07:42.879
[Helen]
Uh, yeah, sure, you can...

07:42.962 --> 07:45.423
you stay as long as you want.
Is that news?

07:46.383 --> 07:47.801
No. No, no.

07:47.884 --> 07:50.095
No, there's just a brush fire
near the Getty.

07:50.178 --> 07:51.554
Okay.

07:52.764 --> 07:54.015
All right. Come on, guys.

07:54.099 --> 07:55.058
Let's go. You're late.

07:55.141 --> 07:56.559
Right.

07:58.103 --> 08:00.522
Hey, are you gonna be here
when I get back?

08:00.605 --> 08:03.608
No. I'll just, uh,
clean up and head out.

08:05.318 --> 08:06.569
Okay.

08:08.113 --> 08:10.240
[water running]

08:10.323 --> 08:12.242
<i>♪ gentle music ♪</i>

08:12.325 --> 08:15.078
<i>♪♪♪</i>

08:33.805 --> 08:36.725
[indistinct chatter]

08:36.808 --> 08:38.059
<i>♪ quiet, suspenseful music ♪</i>

08:38.143 --> 08:41.020
<i>♪♪♪</i>

09:08.840 --> 09:10.717
<i>♪♪♪</i>

09:19.184 --> 09:20.435
All right,
you know what, you guys?

09:20.518 --> 09:22.771
How about we blow off
school today?

09:22.854 --> 09:23.646
Go to the movies
or‐or the beach?

09:23.730 --> 09:26.024
Uh, sorry, Mom.
We've got auditions

09:26.107 --> 09:27.567
for the spring show today.
<i>Camelot.</i>

09:27.650 --> 09:29.110
[Stacey]
Geometry test.

09:29.194 --> 09:30.945
Um, rain check?

09:31.029 --> 09:33.239
Yeah, sure.

09:33.323 --> 09:34.115
[Stacey] Bye, Mom.
Have a good day.

09:34.199 --> 09:36.493
‐Wish me luck.
‐[Helen] Good luck.

09:45.085 --> 09:47.128
Hi. Um, my kids' father

09:47.212 --> 09:49.422
went through
the same thing last year.

09:49.506 --> 09:51.007
We found an amazing
crisis management team.

09:51.091 --> 09:53.968
So just call me, I'll tell you
everything you need to know.

09:54.052 --> 09:55.512
Okay?

09:55.595 --> 09:58.264
<i>♪ quiet, suspenseful music ♪</i>

09:58.348 --> 10:01.351
<i>♪♪♪</i>

10:01.434 --> 10:03.561
[engine revving]

10:05.730 --> 10:06.981
[phone beeps]

10:07.065 --> 10:08.900
Siri, call Noah.

10:11.027 --> 10:13.321
[Noah] <i>It's a complete</i>
<i>hatchet job, Helen.</i>

10:13.404 --> 10:14.823
<i>Everything in that article</i>
<i>was taken out of context.</i>

10:14.906 --> 10:16.741
Well, r‐read it to me.

10:16.825 --> 10:19.661
<i>I'm not sure that's a great</i>
<i>idea while you're driving.</i>

10:21.454 --> 10:23.248
Well, the traffic is insane.

10:23.331 --> 10:26.376
I'm not going anywhere,
so please read it.

10:26.459 --> 10:28.753
[sighs]
<i>"Can this man be redeemed?"</i>

10:28.837 --> 10:30.672
<i>That's over a picture</i>
<i>of my mug shot,</i>

10:30.755 --> 10:32.674
<i>and then: "With a highly</i>
<i>anticipated new novel</i>

10:32.757 --> 10:35.218
<i>and a glitzy</i>
<i>Hollywood adaptation</i>

10:35.301 --> 10:36.719
<i>of his best‐selling last book</i>
<i>in the works,</i>

10:36.803 --> 10:39.347
<i>Noah Solloway is poised</i>
<i>for a comeback.</i>

10:39.430 --> 10:41.349
<i>But in today's climate,</i>
<i>does a man like him</i>

10:41.432 --> 10:43.560
<i>actually deserve one?"</i>

10:43.643 --> 10:45.186
<i>See, from the start,</i>
<i>that premise</i>

10:45.270 --> 10:46.104
<i>is completely misleading.</i>

10:46.187 --> 10:48.314
<i>I went to prison</i>
<i>for a hit‐and‐run,</i>

10:48.398 --> 10:50.567
<i>not sexual harassment;</i>
<i>it's unethical journalism.</i>

10:50.650 --> 10:53.278
[quietly] Oh, my God.
I'm gonna fucking kill you.

10:53.361 --> 10:54.529
<i>What did you say?</i>

10:54.612 --> 10:55.989
Nothing. Just nothing.

10:56.072 --> 10:57.740
Go on.

10:57.824 --> 11:00.201
<i>"Over the course</i>
<i>of my reporting on Solloway,</i>

11:00.285 --> 11:02.745
<i>six women, three of whom</i>
<i>wish to remain anonymous...</i>

11:02.829 --> 11:04.956
‐What?!
<i>‐...came forward</i>
<i>to describe a pattern</i>

11:05.039 --> 11:06.916
‐[sirens approaching]
<i>‐ranging from</i>
<i>inappropriate comments</i>

11:07.000 --> 11:09.043
<i>to unwanted advances</i>
<i>to emotionally..."</i>

11:09.127 --> 11:10.044
[fire truck horn honks]

11:11.462 --> 11:13.047
Ugh, Jesus, Noah.
All right, stop.

11:13.131 --> 11:16.217
Wait, just stop.
Stop talking. Wait.

11:16.301 --> 11:17.427
[sirens fade in distance]

11:17.510 --> 11:20.680
<i>♪ quiet, somber music ♪</i>

11:20.763 --> 11:21.848
<i>♪♪♪</i>

11:24.642 --> 11:27.020
How could you not have known?

11:29.272 --> 11:30.732
‐Noah?
‐[sighs] <i>Gottlief said</i>
<i>he could get</i>

11:30.815 --> 11:33.818
<i>the women</i>
<i>to retract their stories.</i>

11:36.821 --> 11:39.157
So you did know.

11:39.240 --> 11:40.366
And you lied to me.

11:40.450 --> 11:42.160
I asked you point‐blank,
"Was this was a #MeToo story?"

11:42.243 --> 11:44.787
and you said no.

11:50.877 --> 11:54.088
Uh, it should not be this hard
to tell the truth, Noah.

11:54.172 --> 11:56.174
It just... it just shouldn't be.

11:56.257 --> 11:57.759
<i>I'm sorry, Helen.</i>

11:57.842 --> 11:58.968
Just keep reading.

12:04.015 --> 12:05.558
<i>"'The relationship between</i>
<i>a book publicist and client</i>

12:05.642 --> 12:07.602
<i>is, by necessity, intimate.</i>

12:07.685 --> 12:09.437
<i>During a book tour,</i>

12:09.520 --> 12:11.481
<i>you spend an extraordinary</i>
<i>amount of time together.</i>

12:11.564 --> 12:13.441
<i>On flights, in hotels.</i>

12:13.524 --> 12:15.193
<i>He started making</i>
<i>inappropriate comments,</i>

12:15.276 --> 12:16.277
[sighs] <i>and then,</i>
<i>on a number of occasions,</i>

12:16.361 --> 12:17.946
<i>he tried to persuade me</i>
<i>to sleep with him.'</i>

12:18.029 --> 12:20.031
<i>Ellery describes an incident</i>
<i>at Williams College:</i>

12:20.114 --> 12:23.785
'Noah had punched out the
school newspaper's book critic

12:23.868 --> 12:25.787
for giving <i>Descent</i>
a bad review.'"

12:25.870 --> 12:27.830
‐Okay. Wait a minute.
‐[engine stops]

12:27.914 --> 12:30.792
Did this really happen?
Did you punch a kid?

12:30.875 --> 12:33.586
No, no. He was, like, 22,
and he absolutely deserved it.

12:33.670 --> 12:36.005
"'The story was
going viral.

12:36.089 --> 12:39.217
We needed to strategize
about how to run interference,

12:39.300 --> 12:40.718
and Noah insisted his
hotel room was the only place

12:40.802 --> 12:43.221
‐private enough to talk.'"
‐Great.

12:43.304 --> 12:44.847
"'When I arrived, I could tell
immediately that he was drunk.

12:44.931 --> 12:47.642
He pulled me into his room,
started kissing me,

12:47.725 --> 12:48.851
‐groping me.'"
‐Seriously?

12:48.935 --> 12:50.311
Helen, this is not
what happened.

12:50.395 --> 12:52.772
‐She was throwing herself at me.
‐Great.

12:52.855 --> 12:53.564
[sighs]
Shit, I lost my place.

12:53.648 --> 12:56.985
Just give me
the fucking thing.

12:57.068 --> 12:58.111
I didn't sleep
with her, Helen.

12:58.194 --> 12:59.988
I know it sounds crazy,
but I think she's doing this

13:00.071 --> 13:02.156
‐as some kind of revenge.
‐Yeah, that does sound crazy.

13:02.240 --> 13:03.324
[phone chiming]

13:03.408 --> 13:05.159
Now my agent is saying
I‐I should release a statement

13:05.243 --> 13:07.870
saying that I respect women
and apologize to those I hurt.

13:07.954 --> 13:10.039
‐Great. Do that.
‐Yeah, but my publisher's

13:10.123 --> 13:12.583
threatening to exercise a
morality clause in my contract.

13:12.667 --> 13:16.170
‐A morality clause?
‐Yeah.

13:16.254 --> 13:17.380
And not publish my book

13:17.463 --> 13:18.339
if all this negative
publicity continues.

13:18.423 --> 13:19.882
Oh, my God.
What are they waiting for?

13:19.966 --> 13:22.218
And then Gottlief says
I shouldn't do anything,

13:22.302 --> 13:25.388
because he thinks there's
potential for a civil suit.

13:25.471 --> 13:26.723
What should I do?

13:26.806 --> 13:28.224
I don't know!

13:28.308 --> 13:29.225
[ringtone playing]

13:29.309 --> 13:30.601
Just shut off your phone!

13:30.685 --> 13:32.854
It's not mine.
It's yours.

13:34.981 --> 13:36.858
Shit.

13:36.941 --> 13:38.901
It's my boss.

13:38.985 --> 13:40.028
Amy, hi.

13:40.111 --> 13:43.281
Um, yeah. I might just be
running a teeny bit late.

13:43.364 --> 13:44.991
But...

13:47.952 --> 13:49.037
Why's that?

13:52.165 --> 13:54.542
Oh.

13:54.625 --> 13:56.586
Yeah. No, he is... he is my...

13:56.669 --> 13:59.213
uh, my ex‐husband.

14:05.511 --> 14:08.389
Okay, makes sense.

14:09.599 --> 14:12.268
Thanks. You, too.

14:12.351 --> 14:13.478
[phone clicks]

14:15.271 --> 14:17.607
[clicks tongue]
Well, that's a record.

14:17.690 --> 14:19.942
I got fired
before I started my job.

14:20.026 --> 14:21.819
[sighs]

14:21.903 --> 14:23.404
'Cause of me?

14:23.488 --> 14:25.239
[Sierra]
Hi.

14:25.323 --> 14:26.699
Hi.

14:27.658 --> 14:28.034
Everything okay?

14:33.206 --> 14:34.665
Yeah, it's fine.

14:34.749 --> 14:36.584
[phone ringing]

14:36.667 --> 14:38.419
Fuck, it's the kids' school.

14:38.503 --> 14:40.213
Hello?

14:40.296 --> 14:41.297
Yeah.

14:41.380 --> 14:43.132
He did what?

14:44.550 --> 14:47.428
Sure. Yeah, I'll‐I'll...

14:47.512 --> 14:48.429
I'll come right over.

14:48.513 --> 14:49.597
Soon as I can. Thanks.

14:49.680 --> 14:52.141
Trevor got in a fight.

14:52.225 --> 14:53.976
‐Oh, my God. Is he okay?
‐They didn't give any detail.

14:54.060 --> 14:55.645
They just told me to come
and pick him up.

14:55.728 --> 14:56.771
No. I'm going.

14:56.854 --> 14:59.315
Yeah, Helen,
the school called me.

14:59.398 --> 15:01.484
‐Yes, because it was
probably your fault.
‐Please.

15:01.567 --> 15:03.569
That may be true, but it's
really important to me

15:03.653 --> 15:04.654
to get to him, to talk
to him, to explain.

15:04.737 --> 15:07.990
Well, that's not
happening.

15:08.074 --> 15:09.325
<i>♪</i> slow, somber music ♪

15:09.408 --> 15:12.245
<i>♪♪♪</i>

15:12.328 --> 15:15.081
[siren wailing faintly
in distance]

15:21.754 --> 15:25.216
I'm sorry about the job.

15:32.807 --> 15:35.768
I worked my ass off
for that job.

15:38.271 --> 15:39.480
I didn't go to Montauk
to plan my daughter's wedding

15:39.564 --> 15:41.649
to get that job.

15:41.732 --> 15:43.734
Do you know how painful
that was for me?

15:44.735 --> 15:45.528
But doesn't matter,
really,

15:45.611 --> 15:46.737
'cause you know what?

15:46.821 --> 15:49.198
No matter how hard I work,

15:49.282 --> 15:52.160
you always manage to find a way
to fuck my shit up.

15:52.243 --> 15:54.620
‐I said I was sorry.
‐Well, if you want to apologize,

15:54.704 --> 15:57.206
why don't you start
with those women?

15:57.290 --> 16:00.459
How can I apologize, Helen,
when I didn't do anything?

16:00.543 --> 16:01.335
Oh, really?
So they're all lying?

16:01.419 --> 16:03.671
‐Why would they do that?
‐I don't know.

16:03.754 --> 16:05.214
That's what I'm trying
to figure out.

16:05.298 --> 16:07.008
Oh, so you didn't sleep
with the student teacher?

16:08.176 --> 16:10.178
It was... it was consensual.

16:10.261 --> 16:12.430
Oh, except you were her boss!

16:12.513 --> 16:15.850
So maybe it didn't feel
consensual to her.

16:15.933 --> 16:18.352
[groans]
And what about Eden?

16:18.436 --> 16:21.522
She came to my room, uninvited,
and we made out for maybe

16:21.606 --> 16:22.607
fucking one minute.
That was it.

16:22.690 --> 16:23.774
But why did you let her in?

16:23.858 --> 16:25.234
Did you think maybe that
might have been a bad idea?

16:25.318 --> 16:28.696
‐Because I was drunk.
‐Well, whose fault is that?

16:28.779 --> 16:30.656
‐Yours, actually! Yes.
‐What?

16:30.740 --> 16:31.616
Earlier in the night,
we went out.

16:31.699 --> 16:33.242
As usual,
you were drinking like a fish.

16:33.326 --> 16:35.703
You got me shit‐faced. That was
why I didn't kick her out

16:35.786 --> 16:36.704
‐immediately!
‐Are you seriously trying

16:36.787 --> 16:38.206
to turn this
around on me?

16:38.289 --> 16:39.749
Your inability
to take responsibility

16:39.832 --> 16:41.667
for your actions
is pathological.

16:41.751 --> 16:44.045
‐Oh, really? Really?!
‐Yeah. Yeah.

16:44.128 --> 16:47.006
Well, maybe 'cause I'm so busy
taking responsibility for yours!

16:47.089 --> 16:49.717
Oh, my God. Fuck you!

16:49.800 --> 16:51.802
<i>♪</i> slow, somber music ♪

16:51.886 --> 16:53.554
<i>♪♪♪</i>

16:57.767 --> 17:02.063
I've done time for a crime
I didn't commit already, Helen.

17:02.146 --> 17:04.232
I'm not
doing it again.

17:04.315 --> 17:06.234
[siren wailing in distance]

17:07.777 --> 17:09.570
[indistinct
police radio chatter]

17:09.654 --> 17:11.447
[horns honking]

17:15.159 --> 17:17.578
‐Excuse me. What's going on?
‐They're shutting down Sunset

17:17.662 --> 17:20.164
to help with evacuations
off the 405.

17:20.248 --> 17:21.582
You got to pull off here
and turn around.

17:21.666 --> 17:23.167
No, I have to go to Brentwood
to get my kids at school.

17:25.461 --> 17:27.004
What do you mean?
I have to get through.

17:27.088 --> 17:28.506
They're about to start
evacuating the schools

17:28.589 --> 17:29.590
‐in Brentwood anyway.
‐Well, if they're evacuating

17:29.674 --> 17:31.092
the schools, then I really
need to get through

17:31.175 --> 17:34.262
so I can, you know,
evacuate my children.

17:34.345 --> 17:35.638
Ma'am, I can't let you through.

17:35.721 --> 17:37.139
Dude, what the fuck
is your problem?

17:37.223 --> 17:38.891
‐Helen.
‐My kids are over there.

17:38.975 --> 17:40.685
‐Helen. Helen, this is...
‐I have to go get them.

17:40.768 --> 17:41.769
This isn't helping.
Come on.

17:41.852 --> 17:42.687
We'll figure
something else out.

17:42.770 --> 17:45.815
I'm sorry, okay? I am.

17:45.898 --> 17:47.984
Let's just go.

17:52.530 --> 17:54.574
Can you call Trevor?

18:01.706 --> 18:03.666
Voice mail.

18:07.545 --> 18:10.172
‐Fuck. Stacey, too.
‐What?

18:10.256 --> 18:11.591
Do we know anyone on the
Westside who could pick 'em up?

18:11.674 --> 18:14.969
Um...

18:15.052 --> 18:15.928
Yeah.

18:16.012 --> 18:17.847
Uh, Brooklyn's mom.

18:18.764 --> 18:19.473
[line ringing]

18:19.557 --> 18:22.393
Good idea.

18:24.562 --> 18:26.022
Um, I'll pack a bag
for the kids

18:26.105 --> 18:27.773
in case we can't
get back over here.

18:27.857 --> 18:29.817
Can you call Whitney,
see what's up with her flight?

18:29.900 --> 18:31.652
Yeah. I'll check in
with Martin, too.

18:31.736 --> 18:33.487
‐[Eddie fussing]
‐[Priya talking playfully]

18:33.571 --> 18:34.572
Priya.

18:34.655 --> 18:35.698
Oh, hi.

18:35.781 --> 18:39.827
Isn't he the most beautiful
baby you've ever seen?

18:39.910 --> 18:41.996
Yeah... he is beautiful, yeah.
Where's Sierra?

18:42.079 --> 18:44.707
‐[phone ringing]
‐Sierra is packing.

18:44.790 --> 18:47.585
‐Hi.
‐[Noah] Hello?

18:47.668 --> 18:49.337
‐Hi.
‐Um, sorry.

18:49.420 --> 18:51.422
Uh, it was starting
to smell like smoke up here.

18:51.505 --> 18:53.299
I wanted to get Eddie
out of the hills.

18:53.382 --> 18:54.842
I didn't want
to bother you guys,

18:54.925 --> 18:57.053
'cause you seemed kind of busy,
so I called Priya.

18:57.136 --> 18:59.597
‐Oh.
‐[Priya] They're going to stay

18:59.680 --> 19:02.266
with Abdul and me
until the smoke clears.

19:02.350 --> 19:04.435
For as long as they like.

19:04.518 --> 19:06.646
The boy should get to know
his grandparents.

19:08.439 --> 19:09.065
Thank you.

19:09.148 --> 19:11.567
Mm‐hmm.
I'll wait outside.

19:11.651 --> 19:13.944
Okay. Be safe.

19:14.028 --> 19:16.197
[sirens wailing, helicopters
whirring in distance]

19:18.616 --> 19:19.950
[door closes]

19:24.872 --> 19:26.540
[door closes]

19:26.624 --> 19:27.917
What's wrong?

19:29.335 --> 19:33.422
Uh, they're changing
the name of my movie.

19:33.506 --> 19:35.299
Who is?

19:35.383 --> 19:37.510
The producers of <i>Descent.</i>
They're...

19:37.593 --> 19:38.803
They're changing the title
to something else,

19:38.886 --> 19:41.263
and they're offering me a buyout
to take my name off the credits.

19:41.347 --> 19:45.518
So... they're erasing me
from my own story.

19:56.278 --> 19:58.114
I'm sorry.

20:01.200 --> 20:03.202
[ringtone playing]

20:06.288 --> 20:06.789
It's Lauren.

20:06.872 --> 20:09.750
Hey, Lauren, what's‐‐

20:11.210 --> 20:12.628
What do you mean?

20:14.672 --> 20:17.508
Well, where did they go?
I... Yeah.

20:17.591 --> 20:18.592
Okay. I gotta...
Yeah. Of course.

20:18.676 --> 20:21.095
Uh, bye.

20:21.178 --> 20:23.764
Um, Trevor and Stacey
weren't at school.

20:23.848 --> 20:25.141
What? Where are they?

20:25.224 --> 20:26.767
I don't know. Brooklyn said
someone else picked them up,

20:26.851 --> 20:28.436
but he doesn't know who.

20:28.519 --> 20:30.187
Okay, I'll call Trevor,
you call Stacey.

20:30.271 --> 20:32.773
[line ringing]

20:36.527 --> 20:38.487
‐It's just a voice mail.
‐It's just ringing.

20:38.571 --> 20:40.656
I don't understand.
Where would they go?

20:40.740 --> 20:42.992
‐The school wouldn't have
let them just go.
‐Well, they're teenagers.

20:43.075 --> 20:44.744
They can go
when they want to go.

20:44.827 --> 20:47.246
I don't... I don't un...
I mean, no one's texted me.

20:47.329 --> 20:48.706
Anyone else who could
have picked them up?

20:48.789 --> 20:49.790
I don't know.
I mean, I‐I‐I don't...

20:49.874 --> 20:52.001
I have this, um...
the‐the tracking app thingy.

20:52.084 --> 20:54.962
I don't... Can you do that?

20:55.045 --> 20:56.839
‐Let me see.
‐I've never used it.

20:56.922 --> 20:59.467
‐Okay, it's finding Trevor.
‐Okay.

21:00.718 --> 21:02.178
That's weird.

21:02.261 --> 21:04.054
‐What is?
‐Why is he in Malibu?

21:06.140 --> 21:09.185
‐Oh, my God.
‐What?

21:11.187 --> 21:13.981
They're at Sasha's.

21:14.064 --> 21:14.815
I mean, what the fuck?

21:14.899 --> 21:18.235
[phone clicking]

21:18.319 --> 21:19.695
[line ringing]

21:19.779 --> 21:21.781
Hi. Do you have my kids?

21:21.864 --> 21:23.491
[phone ringing]

21:23.574 --> 21:27.495
No, I don't want to FaceTime.
I don't want to FaceTime.

21:27.578 --> 21:31.665
<i>Hey, hey, I just want you</i>
<i>to see that your kids are fine.</i>

21:31.749 --> 21:33.167
<i>They're happy, safe.</i>

21:33.250 --> 21:33.751
<i>Look. Hey, kids,</i>
<i>say hi to your mother.</i>

21:33.834 --> 21:35.085
Hi, guys.

21:35.169 --> 21:37.838
‐Look, Sasha.
<i>‐Yes?</i>

21:37.922 --> 21:40.508
You cannot just get my
fucking kids without telling me.

21:40.591 --> 21:41.675
<i>I tried calling you,</i>

21:41.759 --> 21:44.261
<i>but your phone kept going</i>
<i>straight to voice mail.</i>

21:44.345 --> 21:45.846
<i>Listen, the city's gridlocked,</i>

21:45.930 --> 21:47.389
<i>and‐and I'm sending over</i>
<i>a helicopter.</i>

21:47.473 --> 21:48.682
You're sending
a helicopter where?

21:48.766 --> 21:50.392
<i>To get you.</i>

21:50.476 --> 21:52.019
<i>Yeah, I've‐I've checked it</i>
<i>with my security guys.</i>

21:52.102 --> 21:53.437
<i>There's a landing pad</i>
<i>just up the...</i>

21:53.521 --> 21:54.814
<i>the hill from your house.</i>

21:54.897 --> 21:56.273
Yeah, I can't...
I can't do that.

21:56.357 --> 21:57.900
I have a house full of people.

21:57.983 --> 21:59.193
[laughs]
<i>Of course you do.</i>

21:59.276 --> 22:01.070
<i>What else is new?</i>
<i>So, who's there?</i>

22:01.153 --> 22:02.738
<i>Perhaps we can</i>
<i>squeeze them in, too.</i>

22:02.822 --> 22:03.823
Go. Be with the kids.

22:05.282 --> 22:06.367
<i>‐Is that Noah?</i>
‐Yes!

22:06.450 --> 22:08.536
<i>What the fuck</i>
<i>is he doing there?</i>

22:08.619 --> 22:10.538
<i>Helen, have you...</i>
<i>have you watched the news?</i>

22:10.621 --> 22:12.206
<i>Have you seen what</i>
<i>he's being accused of?</i>

22:12.289 --> 22:14.542
Yeah, that's why
he's here, Sasha,

22:14.625 --> 22:17.086
so we can figure out
how to deal with our children.

22:17.169 --> 22:19.255
<i>I just told you,</i>
<i>your kids are fine.</i>

22:19.338 --> 22:20.798
<i>Okay? They're doing great.</i>

22:20.881 --> 22:22.091
<i>But if you rather want</i>
<i>to stay there</i>

22:22.174 --> 22:23.843
<i>and help your ex‐husband</i>

22:23.926 --> 22:25.636
<i>deal with the fact</i>
<i>that he's just made a fool</i>

22:25.719 --> 22:26.720
<i>of your whole family,</i>
<i>that's your choice.</i>

22:26.804 --> 22:29.056
<i>The helicopter will be there</i>
<i>in 20 minutes.</i>

22:29.139 --> 22:30.599
<i>I suggest you get on it.</i>

22:30.683 --> 22:33.143
[phone beeps]

22:33.227 --> 22:35.354
You should go.

22:39.066 --> 22:40.484
What about you?

22:40.568 --> 22:42.278
I'll be okay.
I'm gonna keep trying Whitney.

22:42.361 --> 22:45.406
Maybe I'll just go
to the airport and wait.

22:45.489 --> 22:47.950
I've got her
flight number somewhere.

22:48.033 --> 22:50.744
I think I should talk to her
in person when she lands.

22:53.414 --> 22:54.498
She probably has
a lot of questions.

22:59.211 --> 23:01.046
Thank you.

23:01.130 --> 23:03.257
For what?

23:03.340 --> 23:05.467
For this morning, today.

23:05.551 --> 23:07.928
All I did was yell at you.

23:08.012 --> 23:09.805
<i>♪ quiet, gentle music ♪</i>

23:09.889 --> 23:12.683
<i>♪♪♪</i>

23:14.059 --> 23:15.728
You're such
a great mother, Helen.

23:20.232 --> 23:22.943
We've got four
great kids, and...

23:23.027 --> 23:25.029
I know it's not because of me.

23:27.114 --> 23:29.241
I'm very grateful.

23:33.203 --> 23:35.331
[helicopter whirring]

23:36.498 --> 23:38.459
<i>♪ somber music ♪</i>

23:38.542 --> 23:39.627
<i>♪♪♪</i>

23:54.558 --> 23:55.684
<i>♪♪♪</i>

24:09.490 --> 24:10.824
[door closes]

24:10.908 --> 24:13.077
[newswoman] <i>There are several</i>
<i>major fires blanketing</i>

24:13.160 --> 24:14.536
<i>the stretch between</i>
<i>Westwood and Ventura County.</i>

24:14.620 --> 24:17.331
<i>Helicopters are still</i>
<i>trying to get</i>

24:17.414 --> 24:20.668
<i>these wildfires under control</i>
<i>and they continue to drop</i>

24:20.751 --> 24:24.421
<i>gallons of water and retardant</i>
<i>onto the fires. Uh...</i>

24:24.505 --> 24:26.632
Hey, guys. You okay?

24:26.715 --> 24:28.384
We're fine.

24:28.467 --> 24:30.719
Trevor, let me see.
What happened? Trevor.

24:30.803 --> 24:34.014
Apparently, Brooklyn said
some shit about Dad.

24:34.098 --> 24:36.016
Trevor hit him,
and he hit Trevor back.

24:37.101 --> 24:38.185
Honey, I'm so sorry.

24:38.268 --> 24:40.104
Yeah, well, it's not your fault
Dad fucks everything up.

24:40.187 --> 24:42.898
[Sasha]
Who's hungry?

24:42.982 --> 24:44.733
Hey, Helen, you made it.

24:44.817 --> 24:46.026
‐Hey.
‐Great.

24:46.110 --> 24:49.196
‐Trevor, can you take this?
‐Yeah.

24:49.279 --> 24:51.198
‐Talk to you for a second?
‐Sure.

24:53.242 --> 24:54.702
[sighs]

24:54.785 --> 24:57.121
Listen... I'm really sorry

24:57.204 --> 25:00.833
that I just went
and got your kids like that.

25:00.916 --> 25:03.627
But the truth is that
Trevor called me and told me

25:03.711 --> 25:04.461
that Noah was at your house

25:04.545 --> 25:07.131
and that he didn't want
to see him.

25:07.214 --> 25:11.093
So he asked me to come
and get him and Stacey.

25:11.176 --> 25:12.219
Really?

25:12.302 --> 25:15.514
Yeah. And I didn't want
to tell you over the phone.

25:15.597 --> 25:18.726
And I'm also sorry
about last night.

25:18.809 --> 25:21.562
I‐I‐I was exhausted, and...

25:23.772 --> 25:25.691
Listen, I... I love you.

25:25.774 --> 25:29.069
But sometimes it frightens me
how big your world is.

25:29.153 --> 25:32.197
And it's not you
who should change; it's me.

25:32.281 --> 25:35.409
And‐and... and that is why
I‐I‐I did what I did

25:35.492 --> 25:36.660
and went and got your kids,
'cause that is exactly

25:36.744 --> 25:38.662
the sort of thing
that you would have done.

25:44.334 --> 25:46.170
Well, I'm sorry, too.

25:48.005 --> 25:49.631
[whispers]
Yeah, okay.

25:50.507 --> 25:53.594
‐Glass of wine?
‐Yeah, please.

25:53.677 --> 25:55.429
All right.

25:55.512 --> 25:57.598
[newsman] <i>Audrey Nelson</i>
<i>is one of the women</i>

25:57.681 --> 25:59.099
<i>accusing Solloway.</i>

25:59.183 --> 26:00.809
<i>We caught up with her</i>
<i>this morning</i>

26:00.893 --> 26:02.770
<i>at the annual</i>
<i>Women in Media Breakfast.</i>

26:02.853 --> 26:06.023
<i>Yes, I was in</i>
<i>his creative writing seminar</i>

26:06.106 --> 26:08.025
<i>my sophomore year</i>
<i>at Livingston.</i>

26:08.108 --> 26:09.443
[newswoman]
<i>Do you have a comment</i>

26:09.526 --> 26:12.112
<i>about the very damning article</i>
<i>that came out this morning</i>

26:12.196 --> 26:12.946
<i>concerning his behavior</i>
<i>toward women?</i>

26:13.030 --> 26:15.866
[Audrey]
<i>All I will say is that</i>

26:15.949 --> 26:17.326
<i>it's always terrifying</i>

26:17.409 --> 26:19.286
<i>to speak out</i>
<i>against powerful men,</i>

26:19.369 --> 26:21.997
<i>especially if you have</i>
<i>been traumatized yourself.</i>

26:22.081 --> 26:23.707
<i>But I have been</i>

26:23.791 --> 26:25.793
<i>very encouraged</i>
<i>by the sisterhood</i>

26:25.876 --> 26:28.212
<i>I've experienced here today</i>
<i>and on Twitter,</i>

26:28.295 --> 26:30.631
<i>and I just think</i>
<i>it's‐it's so important</i>

26:30.714 --> 26:34.134
<i>that we continue to support</i>
<i>and believe each other,</i>

26:34.218 --> 26:36.136
<i>because clearly</i>
<i>there are men out there</i>

26:36.220 --> 26:38.222
<i>‐who just truly hate women.</i>
‐Okay.

26:38.305 --> 26:39.681
You guys, that's enough.
That's enough of this.

26:39.765 --> 26:41.391
Give me that, please.
Just give it to me.

26:41.475 --> 26:42.559
[Stacey]
That woman's a publicity whore.

26:42.643 --> 26:44.603
She's gonna be
on <i>The Talk</i> tomorrow.

26:44.686 --> 26:46.522
She's just trying
to sell books.

26:46.605 --> 26:48.398
Yeah, sure, Stacey,
she's making it all up.

26:48.482 --> 26:49.942
That's what these men say.

26:50.025 --> 26:51.318
They say Dad's
the real victim here.

26:51.401 --> 26:53.779
Oh, Stacey, please, no.

26:53.862 --> 26:54.738
But she's lying, Mom, isn't she?

26:54.822 --> 26:56.949
‐[ringtone playing]
‐Dad doesn't hate women.

26:57.032 --> 26:58.659
Hold on. This might be Whitney.

26:58.742 --> 26:59.827
Hello?

27:02.788 --> 27:05.624
How did you get this number?

27:05.707 --> 27:06.333
No, no comment.

27:06.416 --> 27:09.128
I'll be right back.

27:09.211 --> 27:11.338
Stacey, get off that site.

27:12.005 --> 27:14.299
<i>♪ quiet, tense music ♪</i>

27:14.383 --> 27:16.677
[Sasha]
No. No, no, no, I‐I hear you.

27:16.760 --> 27:19.054
Yeah. Listen,
you're doing a great job.

27:20.264 --> 27:22.015
Well, the title's
a great start.

27:22.099 --> 27:23.642
Now we just have
to bring it home

27:23.725 --> 27:26.144
and‐and get the tosspot's name
off it entirely.

27:26.228 --> 27:28.355
[sighs]

27:29.773 --> 27:32.401
