that evening at Carolina's?

39:47.969 --> 39:49.971
We met her. She was clearly
still traumatized by it.

39:50.054 --> 39:52.932
What did you just say?

39:53.016 --> 39:54.893
What?

39:57.604 --> 40:02.567
How did that reporter know
how to find Eden?

40:02.650 --> 40:05.111
What do you mean?

40:05.194 --> 40:07.906
Eden was his publicist
over ten years ago,

40:07.989 --> 40:10.617
and she just said that she
wasn't looking for this, so...

40:15.622 --> 40:18.041
How did Petra know
how to find her?

40:23.463 --> 40:24.631
Because you told her?

40:27.133 --> 40:29.552
You told her what I said.

40:29.636 --> 40:33.723
Petra called me
to interview me about Noah,

40:33.806 --> 40:34.849
so I told her what I knew.

40:34.933 --> 40:37.852
Oh, my God, do you have
any idea what you've done?

40:37.936 --> 40:41.439
[chuckles] Helen,
I'm not the bad guy here.

40:41.522 --> 40:44.108
If there was no story,
six women,

40:44.192 --> 40:46.152
if there was no story,
this would not stick.

40:46.235 --> 40:48.321
This was the right thing
to do for these women.

40:48.404 --> 40:50.990
"These women"?

40:51.074 --> 40:54.702
Noah's name is off
the movie, his movie,

40:54.786 --> 40:56.829
because that's what you wanted.

40:56.913 --> 40:58.247
[scoffs] As usual,
you've got absolutely

40:58.331 --> 41:01.376
no idea how my business works.

41:01.459 --> 41:04.462
This movie is my baby.

41:04.545 --> 41:06.297
Uh, what about my actual babies?

41:06.381 --> 41:09.342
They're real people, and they
have to live in the real world,

41:09.425 --> 41:10.927
and they're gonna be
scarred for years

41:11.010 --> 41:14.347
because you wanted writing
credit for some idiotic movie?

41:14.430 --> 41:16.474
Hey, this movie is
gonna be quite important.

41:16.557 --> 41:19.143
Oh, my God, you got to be
kidding me. Stop.

41:19.227 --> 41:22.605
[ringtone playing]

41:26.818 --> 41:27.652
No.

41:30.113 --> 41:32.532
No, you don't... don't get it.

41:34.325 --> 41:35.493
Don't.

41:35.576 --> 41:37.412
Helen. Helen.

41:39.414 --> 41:40.957
[sniffles]

41:41.040 --> 41:43.126
Hello?

41:47.422 --> 41:49.549
Okay, I'm on my way.

41:52.301 --> 41:53.970
Hey, kids, get your stuff.
We're going.

41:54.053 --> 41:56.139
[sniffles]

41:57.306 --> 42:00.393
I'm gonna need your fucking car.

42:00.476 --> 42:02.895
<i>♪ "Season in Hell"</i>
<i>by Dum Dum Girls ♪</i>

42:02.979 --> 42:05.273
<i>♪♪♪</i>

42:05.356 --> 42:07.233
<i>♪ From shards ♪</i>

42:07.316 --> 42:10.653
<i>♪ Of broken hearts ♪</i>

42:10.737 --> 42:13.281
<i>♪ Tears from desert eyes ♪</i>

42:13.364 --> 42:15.783
<i>♪ Something new is dreamed ♪</i>

42:18.161 --> 42:22.999
<i>♪ Doesn't dawn look divine? ♪</i>

42:23.082 --> 42:25.710
<i>♪ Lift your gaze ♪</i>

42:25.793 --> 42:30.089
<i>♪ It's the end of days ♪</i>

42:35.178 --> 42:36.137
You're gonna need
to calm down, ma'am.

42:36.220 --> 42:37.263
This is just
the way it is.

42:37.346 --> 42:39.265
‐I understand that.
‐Do you see all these people

42:39.348 --> 42:40.933
behind you? They were all
on the same canceled flight.

42:41.017 --> 42:42.477
You're lucky we can
rebook you at all.

42:42.560 --> 42:44.645
And I appreciate that so much.

42:44.729 --> 42:47.356
I'm just wondering if there's
anything to LAX a little sooner.

42:47.440 --> 42:49.108
Please don't take
that tone with me.

42:49.192 --> 42:52.028
‐I'm sorry. Um...
‐Look, you can take the 5 p. m.,

42:52.111 --> 42:53.863
or you can risk it
and fly standby.

42:53.946 --> 42:55.073
‐It's up to you.
‐[phone chimes]

42:56.866 --> 42:59.160
<i>♪ suspenseful music ♪</i>

43:09.212 --> 43:11.255
Hello? Miss, what
do you want to do?

43:11.339 --> 43:14.425
‐Uh, I'll take the flight.
‐Okay.

43:14.509 --> 43:15.551
Be at the gate an hour
before your flight.

43:15.635 --> 43:17.762
You'll get
reticketed then. Next.

43:17.845 --> 43:19.180
Excuse me.

43:20.098 --> 43:23.017
Sorry.

43:23.101 --> 43:24.310
[mutters]

43:24.393 --> 43:27.063
[whispers]
Oh, my God.

43:27.146 --> 43:29.982
[sighs]

43:33.820 --> 43:35.863
[phone rings, stops]

43:35.947 --> 43:37.782
Go away.

43:39.325 --> 43:41.285
[phone chiming]

43:41.369 --> 43:43.538
Stop.

43:43.621 --> 43:45.998
[phone rings]

43:46.082 --> 43:48.000
Oh, my God.

43:49.293 --> 43:52.130
‐[phone chiming]
‐Stop.

43:52.213 --> 43:54.507
[phone chiming]

43:54.590 --> 43:55.383
‐Stop.
‐[phone rings]

43:55.466 --> 43:58.010
‐[sighs]
‐[phone rings]

43:58.094 --> 43:58.511
Go away.

43:58.594 --> 43:59.804
[phone chiming]

44:03.724 --> 44:04.851
[phone ringing]

44:11.691 --> 44:13.860
[phone clicks]

44:13.943 --> 44:15.778
Hello?

44:20.616 --> 44:23.619
Yeah, I just saw.

44:23.703 --> 44:26.289
Um, I'm... [chuckles]

44:27.874 --> 44:30.293
I don't know how I am, actually.

44:35.631 --> 44:37.300
No, I'm at JFK.

44:37.383 --> 44:38.759
I've...

44:40.553 --> 44:43.598
My flight was canceled.
[chuckles]

44:43.681 --> 44:44.891
Yeah, I'll be here for a while.

44:50.855 --> 44:52.732
Really?

44:52.815 --> 44:54.734
<i>♪ somber music ♪</i>

44:54.817 --> 44:57.486
<i>♪♪♪</i>

44:57.570 --> 44:59.447
Yeah. Yeah, sure.

44:59.530 --> 45:03.451
Um... I'd love to come.

45:06.996 --> 45:08.873
<i>♪♪♪</i>

45:26.015 --> 45:28.184
Oh, love.

45:28.267 --> 45:30.353
[sighs]

45:40.279 --> 45:42.365
[sighs]

45:43.824 --> 45:45.826
[liquid pouring]

45:45.910 --> 45:49.872
[Furkat]
Your father is

45:49.956 --> 45:52.333
a massive prick.

45:52.416 --> 45:54.377
You know that, right?

45:55.378 --> 45:57.421
He is, isn't he?

45:57.505 --> 45:59.507
Mm‐hmm.

45:59.590 --> 46:01.968
I keep thinking
about my siblings.

46:02.051 --> 46:03.469
‐The younger ones.
‐Ugh.

46:03.552 --> 46:05.012
You remember
Trevor and Stacey?

46:05.096 --> 46:07.807
‐Oh, absolutely.
‐Well, they're still in school.

46:07.890 --> 46:09.058
And... [scoffs]

46:09.141 --> 46:10.893
Stacey's 12.

46:10.977 --> 46:13.312
And now, any time
anybody Googles them,

46:13.396 --> 46:14.647
for the rest of their lives...

46:14.730 --> 46:16.274
Or you.

46:18.234 --> 46:21.070
Look, I promise you,

46:21.153 --> 46:23.948
it's all gonna be okay.

46:24.031 --> 46:26.325
And, hey,

46:26.409 --> 46:29.954
you're still a bright,
beautiful young woman

46:30.037 --> 46:32.623
with a massive future.

46:32.707 --> 46:34.000
That hasn't changed.

46:35.876 --> 46:37.837
How could he do this to us?

46:37.920 --> 46:39.922
After everything
he's already put us through.

46:40.006 --> 46:42.883
No, listen, listen.

46:42.967 --> 46:45.386
Oh, God,
this is gonna sound harsh,

46:45.469 --> 46:48.472
but what's happening
with your father is inevitable.

46:48.556 --> 46:51.225
You know? I've never met a man
who's quite so self‐destructive,

46:51.309 --> 46:54.312
so un...

46:54.395 --> 46:56.731
careful.

46:56.814 --> 46:58.357
And you have been
wonderful with him, darling.

46:58.441 --> 46:59.775
You really have.

46:59.859 --> 47:03.029
You've been
the most diligent,

47:03.112 --> 47:06.032
devoted daughter, but sometimes,
with toxic people,

47:06.115 --> 47:08.534
you have to...

47:08.617 --> 47:10.536
make a clean break, you know?

47:10.619 --> 47:12.663
You have to save yourself.

47:15.041 --> 47:18.711
I just spent a week
with him in Montauk,

47:18.794 --> 47:21.213
and he was amazing.

47:21.297 --> 47:24.133
And I‐I thought that he'd
turned a corner or something.

47:24.216 --> 47:25.593
I‐I thought that
we would finally

47:25.676 --> 47:27.470
be able to have a relationship.

47:27.553 --> 47:29.597
What the hell were you doing
in Montauk in December?

47:29.680 --> 47:30.931
You must have been
fucking freezing.

47:36.812 --> 47:40.191
Um, we were planning my wedding.

47:40.274 --> 47:42.026
To who?

47:44.153 --> 47:46.072
Uh, Colin.

47:46.155 --> 47:47.907
He's my boyfriend.

47:47.990 --> 47:50.368
Mazel tov!

47:51.035 --> 47:54.330
Darling, that's fantastic.

47:54.413 --> 47:57.124
Congratulations.

47:57.208 --> 47:58.459
‐Thanks.
‐Oh!

47:58.542 --> 48:00.628
Wow. Um...

48:00.711 --> 48:03.047
Yeah, he's an...
he's an artist, too, actually.

48:03.130 --> 48:04.673
No. You're kidding.

48:04.757 --> 48:06.300
Well, wh‐what sort?

48:06.384 --> 48:09.095
Hang on. Do I know him?

48:09.178 --> 48:11.347
Um, I don't think so.
He's a painter.

48:11.430 --> 48:13.391
‐We met in art school.
‐Well, then, why didn't you

48:13.474 --> 48:15.768
bring him to the thing
at The Broad the other night?

48:15.851 --> 48:17.520
I would have loved
to have met your fiancé.

48:17.603 --> 48:19.522
That would have been a little
awkward, don't you think?

48:19.605 --> 48:21.690
For you, maybe.

48:23.359 --> 48:24.735
Is he any good?

48:26.195 --> 48:28.030
Well, I, um...

48:30.199 --> 48:31.575
He's very private
about his work.

48:31.659 --> 48:33.911
Ah, so he's tortured.

48:33.994 --> 48:39.458
Oh, that's...
that is so romantic.

48:39.542 --> 48:41.544
‐[glass clinks]
‐[liquid pouring]

48:44.755 --> 48:46.424
Young love.

48:46.507 --> 48:49.301
We're actually just getting
married for a green card.

48:49.385 --> 48:50.719
‐Where's he from?
‐[door opens]

48:50.803 --> 48:53.722
‐Ireland. He's Irish.
‐[door closes]

48:59.145 --> 48:59.728
Oh. You're still here?

48:59.812 --> 49:03.441
[Layla]
Oh, um, I'm sorry.

49:03.524 --> 49:07.027
I didn't know if we were
finished working today

49:07.111 --> 49:09.447
or if you were coming back.

49:09.530 --> 49:11.073
So I thought I would wait.

49:11.157 --> 49:13.159
No, I think I've got
what I needed.

49:13.242 --> 49:14.910
You can let yourself out.

49:17.580 --> 49:19.498
<i>♪ tense, atmospheric music ♪</i>

49:19.582 --> 49:22.251
<i>♪♪♪</i>

49:25.963 --> 49:28.340
[door opens, closes]

49:32.052 --> 49:35.222
How come you never
asked me to model?

49:35.306 --> 49:36.891
Huh? Oh, God, no.

49:36.974 --> 49:38.642
You're too good for that.

49:38.726 --> 49:41.103
You say that,
but what does that mean?

49:41.187 --> 49:43.439
Well, most of these girls
aren't very smart,

49:43.522 --> 49:45.649
so modeling
is a good gig for them.

49:45.733 --> 49:47.485
But I want
something more for you.

49:47.568 --> 49:50.362
‐More than...
‐More than a body

49:50.446 --> 49:53.199
that I manipulate for my art.

49:57.953 --> 50:00.539
What about
the other night, then?

50:01.749 --> 50:03.083
[door opens]

50:03.167 --> 50:05.336
‐At the Chateau, when we...
‐[door closes]

50:10.758 --> 50:13.177
‐When we what, Whitney?
‐[elevator clanking]

50:15.137 --> 50:19.308
Wasn't I just a body that you
could manipulate for your art?

50:21.560 --> 50:23.646
You're‐you're talking about
the night we made love.

50:23.729 --> 50:25.606
[laughs]

50:25.689 --> 50:28.901
Uh, we didn't make love.

50:28.984 --> 50:31.737
You fucked me in front of
your rich friend to get him off.

50:31.820 --> 50:33.656
Is that what you think happened?

50:33.739 --> 50:37.243
It's not what I <i>think</i> happened.
I know that that happened.

50:37.326 --> 50:40.412
‐You whored me out.
‐Okay, that's enough!

50:43.707 --> 50:45.125
That's enough.

50:46.794 --> 50:48.671
Now, um...

50:48.754 --> 50:50.923
Listen to me.
[exhales]

50:51.006 --> 50:54.593
I know you're upset about what's
happening with your father.

50:54.677 --> 50:57.471
You're angry and confused and
looking for someone to blame,

50:57.555 --> 50:59.014
but, darling,
don't conflate those feelings

50:59.098 --> 51:01.684
with what happened
at the Chateau,

51:01.767 --> 51:04.770
because that was absolutely
what you wanted.

51:04.853 --> 51:05.771
That's not true.

51:05.854 --> 51:08.774
That is not what I wanted.

51:11.860 --> 51:14.530
Um, so why didn't you go, then?

51:14.613 --> 51:17.116
Huh? For fuck's sake,

51:17.199 --> 51:19.618
why didn't you bring
your fiancé to my opening?

51:19.702 --> 51:21.328
I gave you a plus‐one.

51:23.247 --> 51:24.623
Andrea wanted to come.

51:24.707 --> 51:26.208
Did you, um...

51:26.292 --> 51:28.419
did you tell your fiancé
what happened between us?

51:33.674 --> 51:36.051
Do you know what?
If I were you, Whitney,

51:36.135 --> 51:38.470
I'd think long and hard

51:38.554 --> 51:41.473
before making
accusations.

51:41.557 --> 51:43.726
You need friends right now.

51:43.809 --> 51:45.436
What you should be worried about

51:45.519 --> 51:47.396
is what's happening
with your father.

51:47.479 --> 51:52.484
Very worried, because it could
have severe repercussions

51:52.568 --> 51:53.819
for your own career.

51:53.902 --> 51:55.279
Now, I've been
sitting here all day

51:55.362 --> 51:56.655
since the article came out,

51:56.739 --> 51:59.491
trying to think
how I could help you.

51:59.575 --> 52:00.492
And here's the thing:

52:00.576 --> 52:04.413
Dashiell is opening
a gallery on 21st Street,

52:04.496 --> 52:10.002
and he is planning to have me
as his inaugural artist,

52:10.085 --> 52:13.881
and we had discussed
the possibility of you

52:13.964 --> 52:16.800
curating my first show.

52:16.884 --> 52:21.680
But if that's how you
really feel about him and me,

52:21.764 --> 52:25.309
then perhaps we ought
to revisit that idea.

52:39.823 --> 52:42.618
Why did you hit me in Paris?

52:42.701 --> 52:44.828
<i>♪ tense music ♪</i>

52:44.912 --> 52:46.830
<i>♪♪♪</i>

52:46.914 --> 52:48.207
Hit you?

52:48.666 --> 52:50.376
I didn't.

52:53.879 --> 52:55.756
You did.

52:55.839 --> 52:57.257
I remember.

52:57.341 --> 52:59.968
[chuckles]
Oh, Christ.

53:01.553 --> 53:04.223
Ah, Whitney. I can see
that our little tiff in Paris

53:04.306 --> 53:06.266
has got blown
out of all proportion

53:06.350 --> 53:08.602
inside your
gorgeous little head.

53:08.686 --> 53:11.188
But, darling,
for something so dramatic

53:11.271 --> 53:13.857
to transpire,
there would have to be passion

53:13.941 --> 53:15.651
in the relationship,
and sweet as you are,

53:15.734 --> 53:18.153
I never had those kinds
of feelings for you.

53:26.412 --> 53:28.831
You should, um...
you should probably go.

53:28.914 --> 53:31.041
You don't want to miss
your flight, right?

53:36.672 --> 53:38.132
Okay, um...

53:41.844 --> 53:43.762
Could you at least
take me to the airport?

53:43.846 --> 53:46.140
I just... I don't really want
to leave things like this.

53:46.223 --> 53:48.142
You know, I don't think
that's a great idea.

53:48.225 --> 53:52.646
Um, it was probably a mistake
to invite you over.

53:54.314 --> 53:56.233
I'm in a good place right now.

53:56.316 --> 53:58.610
You know, I'm very...

53:58.694 --> 54:01.238
productive.

54:01.321 --> 54:02.322
I don't...

54:02.406 --> 54:06.452
I don't want to get
trammeled in the past.

54:11.123 --> 54:13.250
[sets down glass]

54:16.420 --> 54:18.422
<i>♪ slow, somber music ♪</i>

54:18.505 --> 54:20.340
<i>♪♪♪</i>

54:46.909 --> 54:49.036
<i>♪♪♪</i>

55:08.680 --> 55:10.098
[sighs]

55:10.182 --> 55:11.892
[cashier]
Ma'am?

55:12.935 --> 55:14.394
[keypad beeping]

55:14.478 --> 55:16.438
[man speaking indistinctly
over P. A.]

55:23.904 --> 55:26.740
[sighs]

55:27.783 --> 55:29.618
[indistinct chatter]

55:36.124 --> 55:38.544
[indistinct chatter]

55:41.129 --> 55:43.298
‐Uh...
‐[tense chatter]

55:45.217 --> 55:47.135
‐Um...
‐Watch it.

55:47.219 --> 55:48.679
[chuckles softly]

55:48.762 --> 55:51.390
[indistinct chatter]

55:51.473 --> 55:53.475
Excuse me.

55:53.559 --> 55:54.476
‐Okay, so you're on the flight.
‐[Whitney] Hello.

55:54.560 --> 55:56.645
I wasn't able
to get you seats together,

55:56.728 --> 55:57.980
‐but you are on.
‐Hi. Excuse me. I‐I'm sorry.

55:58.063 --> 55:59.356
‐We talked about this earlier.
‐Oh, yes, sir, you are also

55:59.439 --> 56:00.857
‐on the list. I'm gonna check...
‐Excuse me, I'm actually...

56:00.941 --> 56:02.150
‐Excuse... Excuse me! Sorry.
‐One second. Give me a moment.

56:02.234 --> 56:05.404
‐Excuse me.
‐Hi. Uh, four hours ago,

56:05.487 --> 56:06.446
you stood right there
and promised me

56:06.530 --> 56:08.282
that I would have a seat
on this flight,

56:08.365 --> 56:09.241
and now I don't see my name,
so how are we gonna

56:09.324 --> 56:11.326
‐solve this problem?
‐I am so sorry.

56:11.410 --> 56:13.412
‐What's your name?
‐Audrey Nelson.

56:13.495 --> 56:16.206
‐Let me take a look, Ms. Nelson.
‐Thank you.

56:17.833 --> 56:19.209
[Audrey sighs]

56:19.876 --> 56:22.796
Sorry.

56:22.879 --> 56:25.591
Sorry. Sorry.

56:25.674 --> 56:27.634
Sorry.
[chuckles softly]

56:27.718 --> 56:29.011
Sorry.

56:30.012 --> 56:31.138
Sorry.

56:31.221 --> 56:32.556
[Audrey]
Why are you sorry?

56:34.099 --> 56:36.685
[chuckles]
Oh, sorry.

56:41.023 --> 56:42.774
<i>♪ quiet, atmospheric music ♪</i>

56:42.858 --> 56:44.985
<i>♪♪♪</i>

56:47.904 --> 56:50.741
[sighs]

57:18.894 --> 57:21.772
<i>♪♪♪</i>

57:50.592 --> 57:51.718
<i>♪♪♪</i>

57:55.263 --> 57:55.597
Hey.

57:58.141 --> 57:59.685
You're Audrey Nelson, right?

57:59.768 --> 58:01.603
Yeah. Hey.

58:01.687 --> 58:02.187
We went to school
together, right?

58:02.270 --> 58:05.774
I'm Whitney... Solloway.

58:07.484 --> 58:08.652
Noah's my dad.

58:11.029 --> 58:12.864
[chuckles]
Hey.

58:12.948 --> 58:14.616
I have an aisle seat in 23.

58:14.700 --> 58:16.868
Do you want to switch?
We'd love to catch up.

58:16.952 --> 58:19.246
Sure.

58:19.329 --> 58:20.539
You girls have fun.

58:20.622 --> 58:22.249
[seat belt clicks]

58:28.004 --> 58:30.424
[scoffs] So, should I
tell the air marshal

58:30.507 --> 58:32.092
to be on standby or...?

58:32.175 --> 58:33.260
[chuckles]
No. You're hilarious.

58:33.343 --> 58:35.387
Hey, I was just actually
catching up with you on Twitter.

58:35.470 --> 58:37.472
Congrats on the new memoir,
by the way.

58:37.556 --> 58:40.600
And, um, I just wanted
to say hi to the woman

58:40.684 --> 58:42.060
who's ruining
my family's life.

58:44.312 --> 58:46.940
Uh, wow.
[stifled laugh]

58:47.023 --> 58:49.901
I was joking, but maybe
I should call the air marshal.

58:51.820 --> 58:54.030
Look, here's the thing.

58:54.114 --> 58:55.699
I have three siblings in school.

58:55.782 --> 58:57.659
My mom's second husband
just died of pancreatic cancer.

58:57.743 --> 59:01.079
My mom's dad has Alzheimer's.
My mom hasn't worked

59:01.163 --> 59:03.039
in ten years
so that she could raise us.

59:03.123 --> 59:06.084
So we were all kind of counting
on my dad's book to come out.

59:06.168 --> 59:08.462
You know, so my siblings
could stay in school.

59:11.131 --> 59:13.967
Um, that's a lot.

59:14.050 --> 59:16.219
Yeah. And I bet you
never even bothered

59:16.303 --> 59:17.846
to check whether he had kids

59:17.929 --> 59:19.723
before speaking out
against him, did you?

59:23.518 --> 59:24.269
Actually, I knew
he had children.

59:24.352 --> 59:27.439
Did you ever stop to think

59:27.522 --> 59:30.275
how this might affect
other people, besides my father?

59:35.363 --> 59:36.948
Yes, Whitney.

59:37.032 --> 59:38.950
I thought about it
long and hard,

59:39.034 --> 59:41.620
and I decided
that it was worth it.

59:41.703 --> 59:42.871
Wow.

59:42.954 --> 59:45.499
Look, I worshipped your father.

59:45.582 --> 59:48.502
Okay? All I ever wanted
was to be a writer,

59:48.585 --> 59:49.753
and I'd read <i>Descent,</i>
like, a dozen times,

59:49.836 --> 59:54.633
so getting to study
with Noah Solloway was a dream.

59:54.716 --> 59:56.802
So you're mad at my father
because he didn't live up

59:56.885 --> 59:58.345
to your fantasies of him?

59:58.428 --> 1:00:00.305
No, that's not it.

1:00:00.388 --> 1:00:03.016
So, what is it, Audrey?
He didn't like your work?

1:00:03.099 --> 1:00:05.477
He didn't even give
my writing a chance.

1:00:05.560 --> 1:00:07.479
He took one look at me
and decided he knew

1:00:07.562 --> 1:00:10.315
how much I was worth before
he'd read a thing I'd written.

1:00:10.398 --> 1:00:11.900
Why would he do that?

1:00:13.401 --> 1:00:14.694
Because he didn't
respect me, Whitney.

1:00:14.778 --> 1:00:17.572
Well, maybe your writing
just wasn't very good.

1:00:17.656 --> 1:00:19.199
Did you ever consider that?

1:00:19.282 --> 1:00:21.243
[laughs]

1:00:23.078 --> 1:00:24.704
Yeah, yeah. You're right.

1:00:24.788 --> 1:00:28.375
At the time,
it‐it really wasn't.

1:00:28.458 --> 1:00:30.710
I was very young
when I was in Noah's class,

1:00:30.794 --> 1:00:32.712
and I was honestly desperate
for his guidance,

1:00:32.796 --> 1:00:37.926
but he didn't evaluate my work;
he evaluated me.

1:00:38.009 --> 1:00:39.261
He told me that I had
no inner life.

1:00:39.344 --> 1:00:41.805
Well, do you?

1:00:42.514 --> 1:00:44.766
Everyone has an inner life.

1:00:44.850 --> 1:00:50.063
What he meant was that
I didn't share his inner life

1:00:50.146 --> 1:00:53.066
and that I wasn't trying
hard enough to hide that.

1:00:53.149 --> 1:00:58.363
So, because I was writing about
being young and being female,

1:00:58.446 --> 1:01:01.575
he assumed that I had
nothing interesting to say.

1:01:01.658 --> 1:01:04.703
Have you ever experienced that?

1:01:06.538 --> 1:01:08.915
I mean, look, it just sounds
like he was a shitty professor,

1:01:08.999 --> 1:01:10.041
and I'm sorry
that he hurt your feelings,

1:01:10.125 --> 1:01:12.335
but that's not a reason
to ruin his entire career.

1:01:12.419 --> 1:01:14.921
‐It's not?
‐No.

1:01:15.005 --> 1:01:17.090
Why not?

1:01:17.966 --> 1:01:20.468
Why didn't you just
drop the class?

1:01:20.552 --> 1:01:24.890
I did. Well, actually, first,
I complained to my dean,

1:01:24.973 --> 1:01:27.601
who told me that I needed
to grow a thicker skin.

1:01:27.684 --> 1:01:29.311
So, then I dropped the class.

1:01:29.394 --> 1:01:32.439
And it was a class
that I needed for my major,

1:01:32.522 --> 1:01:34.441
so I dropped that, too.

1:01:34.524 --> 1:01:38.361
And I stopped writing
for three years,

1:01:38.445 --> 1:01:41.281
and I went into
a pretty serious depression.

1:01:41.364 --> 1:01:43.950
That's terrible, Audrey, but
that's not my father's fault.

1:01:45.869 --> 1:01:47.746
So, whose fault is it?

1:01:47.829 --> 1:01:48.705
I don't know.

1:01:48.788 --> 1:01:51.249
I don't think
it's anybody's fault.

1:01:51.333 --> 1:01:53.043
I think it's just
something that happened.

1:01:54.169 --> 1:01:56.254
Right. Okay, right.

1:01:56.338 --> 1:01:59.257
That is exactly what
I thought, too, at the time.

1:01:59.341 --> 1:02:04.304
But the truth is that the way
that Noah spoke to me,

1:02:04.387 --> 1:02:05.680
the way that he treated me

1:02:05.764 --> 1:02:11.603
confirmed my own worst fears
about myself.

1:02:11.686 --> 1:02:14.898
Things that I had heard in one
way or another my entire life.

1:02:14.981 --> 1:02:16.858
That I was worthless

1:02:16.942 --> 1:02:20.946
and stupid and not hot enough,

1:02:21.029 --> 1:02:24.866
just generally a waste of space.

1:02:24.950 --> 1:02:27.869
And it really wasn't until
I started writing my memoir

1:02:27.953 --> 1:02:30.705
that I even began to ask myself,

1:02:30.789 --> 1:02:35.627
"Okay, why have I thought
this way all this time?

1:02:35.710 --> 1:02:38.505
Why did I just assume
that the problem is me?

1:02:38.588 --> 1:02:41.758
Why do I have to
leave the class?

1:02:41.841 --> 1:02:46.471
And why is the way that Noah
treated me considered normal?"

1:02:46.554 --> 1:02:49.099
Think about it, Whitney, okay?

1:02:49.182 --> 1:02:54.187
We give men like him
such unbelievable rope.

1:02:54.270 --> 1:02:56.648
We will do anything‐‐

1:02:56.731 --> 1:02:59.317
anything‐‐ to protect their egos

1:02:59.401 --> 1:03:03.196
when they continuously
and carelessly destroy ours

1:03:03.279 --> 1:03:04.614
without consequence.

1:03:04.698 --> 1:03:07.033
I mean, why? Why does it
have to be like that?

1:03:07.117 --> 1:03:08.618
I agree.

1:03:08.702 --> 1:03:11.204
The world is a shitty place,
and it's not fair.

1:03:11.287 --> 1:03:13.790
But I still feel like
you're using your private beef

1:03:13.873 --> 1:03:14.874
with my father
to promote your book sales,

1:03:14.958 --> 1:03:18.753
and that's just...
that's fucking bullshit.

1:03:20.964 --> 1:03:22.382
Wow.

1:03:24.175 --> 1:03:26.094
Someone really did
a number on you.

1:03:27.429 --> 1:03:29.347
Look, I've had tough experiences

1:03:29.431 --> 1:03:31.433
with older men, too‐‐
teachers, bosses‐‐

1:03:31.516 --> 1:03:33.518
but I'm adult enough to admit
that sometimes the problem

1:03:33.601 --> 1:03:35.937
was just that I wanted to
fuck them and I shouldn't have.

1:03:36.021 --> 1:03:38.106
Or I wanted them to fuck me
and they didn't.

1:03:38.189 --> 1:03:39.774
Or maybe it's just
that sometimes,

1:03:39.858 --> 1:03:41.526
relationships
between men and women

1:03:41.609 --> 1:03:43.903
get weird and awkward,
and that's normal.

1:03:43.987 --> 1:03:45.280
But that doesn't mean
all men should burn.

1:03:45.363 --> 1:03:48.908
Mm‐hmm. Okay.

1:03:48.992 --> 1:03:52.162
I wanted to sleep with your dad.
You're right.

1:03:52.245 --> 1:03:55.832
And, yeah, he didn't want
to sleep with me back,

1:03:55.915 --> 1:03:57.208
and that hurt my feelings.

1:03:57.292 --> 1:04:01.713
But, Whitney, when you want
to sleep with these older guys,

1:04:01.796 --> 1:04:05.216
ask yourself, like, what are you
really attracted to?

1:04:05.300 --> 1:04:08.386
Is it them,
or is it their power

1:04:08.470 --> 1:04:11.723
and their authority,
their agency in the world?

1:04:11.806 --> 1:04:14.517
Like, how they can get
the kind of shit done

1:04:14.601 --> 1:04:16.102
that you can only dream of,
and they do it

1:04:16.186 --> 1:04:19.314
without even breaking a sweat
because the world

1:04:19.397 --> 1:04:22.400
just offers itself up to them
on a silver platter.

1:04:22.484 --> 1:04:25.278
Ask yourself,
do you really want to fuck them,

1:04:25.361 --> 1:04:27.489
or do you want to be them?

1:04:33.078 --> 1:04:35.246
Look, I'm sorry
about your family.

1:04:35.330 --> 1:04:37.165
I really am.

1:04:37.248 --> 1:04:38.958
And, yeah,

1:04:39.042 --> 1:04:41.795
I‐I considered not speaking up
for this very reason,

1:04:41.878 --> 1:04:44.380
'cause I thought...
[sighs]

1:04:44.464 --> 1:04:48.093
"God, what if my individual
trauma is not worth blowing up

1:04:48.176 --> 1:04:49.552
anyone else's life
in order to tell?"

1:04:49.636 --> 1:04:52.722
But if we all do that,

1:04:52.806 --> 1:04:56.601
if we all think like that,

1:04:56.684 --> 1:04:59.771
then none of these stories
are ever gonna get told.

1:04:59.854 --> 1:05:03.650
So, when does it become enough?

1:05:03.733 --> 1:05:05.610
When does our need
to tell our stories

1:05:05.693 --> 1:05:08.279
become greater than their need

1:05:08.363 --> 1:05:10.031
to preserve
the status quo?

1:05:10.115 --> 1:05:12.450
Is it when we're abused
or when we're raped?

1:05:12.534 --> 1:05:13.785
Or is that even enough?

1:05:13.868 --> 1:05:16.162
Because, honestly, it depends
on the man in question, right?

1:05:18.540 --> 1:05:21.126
Really, what I'm saying
is that this is the problem.

1:05:21.209 --> 1:05:26.297
We constantly debate whether
we even have the right to speak.

1:05:26.381 --> 1:05:29.884
Like, we, we monitor what we say
and our choice of words.

1:05:29.968 --> 1:05:32.804
And, oh, are we sitting,
or are we standing?

1:05:32.887 --> 1:05:34.222
And, oh, we're...
if we're sitting,

1:05:34.305 --> 1:05:35.807
well, how are we sitting?

1:05:35.890 --> 1:05:38.017
And if we're standing,
well, what are we wearing?

1:05:38.101 --> 1:05:39.602
And are our voices
pitched just right?

1:05:39.686 --> 1:05:40.770
I mean, think about
the mental gymnastics

1:05:40.854 --> 1:05:44.023
that you have to do in order
to just have a conversation.

1:05:44.107 --> 1:05:46.192
And now imagine
what it would be like

1:05:46.276 --> 1:05:49.279
if we lived in a world where we
didn't have to do any of that.

1:05:49.362 --> 1:05:51.823
Where we can just speak.

1:05:51.906 --> 1:05:54.993
We're not the problem, Whitney.

1:05:55.076 --> 1:05:56.286
They are.

1:05:56.369 --> 1:05:59.998
All I want is just
to live in a world

1:06:00.081 --> 1:06:02.667
where we're not, like,
weird second‐class citizens

1:06:02.750 --> 1:06:05.420
whose first job is
to make men comfortable,

1:06:05.503 --> 1:06:08.214
and then we'll be
allowed to speak.

1:06:08.298 --> 1:06:09.883
[sighs]

1:06:12.427 --> 1:06:14.721
And, yeah, I think
that your dad is

1:06:14.804 --> 1:06:18.516
an impediment to that world.

1:06:18.600 --> 1:06:21.686
And from what I read
in that article,

1:06:21.769 --> 1:06:24.772
I'm not the only one.

1:06:24.856 --> 1:06:28.359
So... I felt that I needed

1:06:28.443 --> 1:06:31.029
to say something, and I...

1:06:31.112 --> 1:06:34.574
I just hope that
you can understand that.

1:06:34.657 --> 1:06:36.576
<i>♪ somber music ♪</i>

1:06:36.659 --> 1:06:38.786
<i>♪♪♪</i>

1:06:47.378 --> 1:06:48.630
She lives.

1:06:49.464 --> 1:06:52.342
I told you my flight
was canceled.

1:06:52.425 --> 1:06:54.719
Yeah, and then you went
radio silent.

1:06:55.970 --> 1:06:59.224
I've been worried
about you, Whit.

1:06:59.307 --> 1:07:02.560
I'm sorry. I'm so tired.
I had the craziest day.

1:07:02.644 --> 1:07:04.187
I just need to go to bed.

1:07:05.521 --> 1:07:07.523
‐Wait a bit.
‐Come on, Colin.

1:07:09.442 --> 1:07:10.818
[sighs]

1:07:11.945 --> 1:07:13.655
What's going on with you?

1:07:13.738 --> 1:07:16.449
We barely spoke the entire
time you were in Montauk.

1:07:21.955 --> 1:07:23.998
[exhales sharply]

1:07:25.166 --> 1:07:26.918
Nothing's going on
with me, Colin,

1:07:27.001 --> 1:07:28.795
except for the fact
that my father just got

1:07:28.878 --> 1:07:30.630
Harvey Weinstein'd,
and my whole future

1:07:30.713 --> 1:07:32.966
just got flushed
down the toilet.

1:07:34.509 --> 1:07:37.262
And I don't really think I
owe you anything at the moment.

1:07:37.345 --> 1:07:38.930
Not even a conversation.

1:07:39.013 --> 1:07:41.182
‐I'm going to bed.
‐I'm sorry, but you can't.

1:07:41.266 --> 1:07:43.268
I know you've had a long day,
and I'm sure you're very tired,

1:07:43.351 --> 1:07:44.936
but we have to talk.

1:07:45.019 --> 1:07:48.439
You can't just disappear,
ignore my calls and texts.

1:07:48.523 --> 1:07:49.941
That's not okay.

1:07:50.024 --> 1:07:52.151
I'm about to be your husband,
for Christ's sake.

1:07:58.533 --> 1:08:00.410
I can't do this.

1:08:01.869 --> 1:08:03.621
You can't do what?
Can't talk to me?

1:08:04.872 --> 1:08:06.291
I can't marry you.

1:08:14.507 --> 1:08:16.426
Okay.

1:08:18.136 --> 1:08:19.846
Why not?

1:08:23.808 --> 1:08:26.394
'Cause I fucked someone else.

1:08:36.195 --> 1:08:37.864
[exhales]

1:08:45.955 --> 1:08:47.290
Who?

1:08:48.666 --> 1:08:51.544
Furkat.

1:08:51.627 --> 1:08:53.004
The photographer?

1:08:53.087 --> 1:08:55.882
We used to date
back in New York.

1:08:55.965 --> 1:08:56.299
What?

1:08:58.217 --> 1:08:59.344
It only happened once.

1:08:59.427 --> 1:09:00.678
That night at The Broad.

1:09:04.432 --> 1:09:06.100
Were you with him today?

1:09:06.184 --> 1:09:07.393
Yes, but nothing happened.

1:09:09.479 --> 1:09:10.688
You don't have
to believe me,

1:09:10.772 --> 1:09:12.273
but it's the truth.

1:09:14.650 --> 1:09:16.402
I believe you.

1:09:25.453 --> 1:09:27.163
Do you love him, then?

1:09:28.706 --> 1:09:30.375
No.

1:09:30.458 --> 1:09:32.335
He's an asshole.

1:09:32.960 --> 1:09:35.004
But clearly, so am I.

1:09:35.088 --> 1:09:38.383
You should leave me, Colin.

1:09:38.466 --> 1:09:40.802
We should break up.

1:09:42.804 --> 1:09:43.346
If that's what you want.

1:09:45.264 --> 1:09:47.558
Why isn't it what you want?

1:09:50.395 --> 1:09:53.398
I guess I'd like to know
what's going on first.

1:09:54.691 --> 1:09:56.442
If we can fix things.

1:09:56.526 --> 1:09:58.653
Right.

1:09:58.736 --> 1:10:00.405
Right, because,
if we don't fix things,

1:10:00.488 --> 1:10:01.614
you get deported.

1:10:01.698 --> 1:10:04.409
Jesus!

1:10:04.492 --> 1:10:06.244
Fucking Christ, Whitney,

1:10:06.327 --> 1:10:08.955
is that really what
you think this is about?

1:10:09.038 --> 1:10:10.206
A green card?

1:10:10.289 --> 1:10:11.290
Isn't it?

1:10:11.374 --> 1:10:15.044
I hate this
godforsaken country.

1:10:15.128 --> 1:10:17.755
I'd love to go home.

1:10:17.839 --> 1:10:20.216
I'm not with you
because I need a green card.

1:10:20.299 --> 1:10:23.636
I need a green card because
I fucking want to be with you.

1:10:28.933 --> 1:10:31.102
[Colin sighs heavily]

1:10:31.185 --> 1:10:33.187
<i>♪ quiet, atmospheric music ♪</i>

1:10:33.271 --> 1:10:34.355
<i>♪♪♪</i>

1:10:52.749 --> 1:10:55.835
[sniffles, sighs]

1:11:08.097 --> 1:11:09.474
I'm sorry.

1:11:12.310 --> 1:11:15.188
I know I'm an
impossibly slow painter.

1:11:16.689 --> 1:11:18.733
I wish I could just
turn out work

1:11:18.816 --> 1:11:20.401
like some of my peers,
like Furkat,

1:11:20.485 --> 1:11:22.987
an‐and sell them
for millions of dollars

1:11:23.070 --> 1:11:25.865
and buy us a house.

1:11:25.948 --> 1:11:28.951
I will get there someday.
I know I will.

1:11:29.035 --> 1:11:31.829
But just don't fucking
give up on me yet.

1:11:31.913 --> 1:11:34.499
I'm so... I'm so sorry.

1:11:34.582 --> 1:11:37.794
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

1:11:41.714 --> 1:11:43.883
I love you so much.

1:11:48.805 --> 1:11:50.932
<i>♪♪♪</i>

1:11:58.648 --> 1:12:01.567
‐[knocking on door]
‐[Noah] Whitney, you in there?

1:12:01.651 --> 1:12:03.402
Whitney?

1:12:06.447 --> 1:12:07.365
Oh, thank God.

1:12:07.448 --> 1:12:09.075
What's up?

1:12:09.158 --> 1:12:10.701
I'm sorry, uh, just showing up.

1:12:10.785 --> 1:12:12.870
We didn't know where you were.
We were worried.

1:12:12.954 --> 1:12:14.872
Oh, okay, well, I'm fine,
so you can leave.

1:12:14.956 --> 1:12:16.040
No, I need to talk.
I need to talk.

1:12:16.123 --> 1:12:19.168
You've seen
the news, right?

1:12:19.252 --> 1:12:20.461
Of course.

1:12:20.545 --> 1:12:24.006
Uh, look, it's terrible,
but I need you to know

1:12:24.090 --> 1:12:25.716
there is... that article,
the allegations,

1:12:25.800 --> 1:12:28.469
what those women are saying,
there is no truth in it at all.

1:12:30.012 --> 1:12:31.305
Can I come in?

1:12:31.389 --> 1:12:33.057
Please?

1:12:34.183 --> 1:12:36.394
Um...

1:12:37.436 --> 1:12:38.896
[clicks tongue]

1:12:40.648 --> 1:12:43.442
Uh, Whitney,
the‐the real story is‐is...

1:12:43.526 --> 1:12:45.862
it's just much,
much more complicated.

1:12:45.945 --> 1:12:47.113
Look, that doesn't matter.

1:12:47.196 --> 1:12:49.532
The point is, I'm your
father and I love you

1:12:49.615 --> 1:12:51.284
and you don't need to worry,

1:12:51.367 --> 1:12:53.244
because your mom and I,
we're gonna take care of this.

1:12:53.327 --> 1:12:54.036
How?

1:12:54.120 --> 1:12:55.329
What do you mean?

1:12:55.413 --> 1:12:57.164
How are you gonna
take care of it?

1:12:57.248 --> 1:12:58.457
Well, we're gonna fight it.

1:12:58.541 --> 1:13:00.751
You really think that's
such a good idea?

1:13:00.835 --> 1:13:01.919
Well, what choice
have I got?

1:13:02.003 --> 1:13:03.212
I... we're not gonna
let these women

1:13:03.296 --> 1:13:03.629
ruin our lives.

1:13:05.965 --> 1:13:07.091
I'm so tired.
I have to go to sleep.

1:13:07.174 --> 1:13:09.260
‐No, okay. No, of course.
‐I don't want to talk about it.

1:13:09.343 --> 1:13:10.970
‐I'm sorry. I'm sorry.
‐Okay, Whitney, I understand.

1:13:11.053 --> 1:13:12.763
‐I just need you to know‐‐
‐Mr. Solloway, it's very late.

1:13:14.390 --> 1:13:16.183
You should go.

1:13:17.184 --> 1:13:18.144
Hi, Colin. Hi.

1:13:18.227 --> 1:13:19.520
This is, uh, no disrespect.

1:13:19.604 --> 1:13:21.272
This is just between me
and my daughter, okay?

1:13:21.355 --> 1:13:22.940
She doesn't want
to talk to you.

1:13:23.024 --> 1:13:24.358
She just asked you
to leave.

1:13:26.235 --> 1:13:27.111
[loud knock on door]

1:13:27.194 --> 1:13:28.029
‐[sighs]
‐Oh, my God.

1:13:28.112 --> 1:13:31.908
Thank God. Whitney.

1:13:31.991 --> 1:13:34.201
Oh, my God, we were
so worried about you.

1:13:34.285 --> 1:13:35.953
[Whitney]
Uh, okay.

1:13:36.037 --> 1:13:38.122
‐Well, I'm fine.
‐Okay.

1:13:38.205 --> 1:13:39.624
All right, listen,
I need to talk to everybody.

1:13:39.707 --> 1:13:41.500
Okay? I just... I need to...
I just... I just...

1:13:41.584 --> 1:13:43.920
I found something out,
and I need to tell all of you.

1:13:44.003 --> 1:13:46.631
So, can we please just
sit down and talk? Please.

1:13:51.135 --> 1:13:53.012
Okay, uh, uh...

1:13:53.095 --> 1:13:55.514
all of this is my fault.

1:13:55.598 --> 1:13:59.393
Everything that's happening
right now is my fault.

1:14:00.394 --> 1:14:00.561
What?

1:14:03.564 --> 1:14:06.067
Because Sasha wants
writing credit

1:14:06.150 --> 1:14:06.901
for your dad's movie.

1:14:06.984 --> 1:14:10.321
And I... he...

1:14:10.404 --> 1:14:13.157
he used something I said
that I should not have said,

1:14:13.240 --> 1:14:14.825
and he gave it
to a reporter,

1:14:14.909 --> 1:14:16.452
and now she's using it
against your father.

1:14:16.535 --> 1:14:19.372
But your dad didn't
do anything wrong.

1:14:19.455 --> 1:14:20.957
They're just spinning it.

1:14:21.040 --> 1:14:23.000
Can you take Stacey
and Trevor for ice cream?

1:14:23.084 --> 1:14:24.043
‐Yeah.
‐No, we're not children.

1:14:24.126 --> 1:14:25.795
‐I want to stay.
‐No, please, I need you to go.

1:14:25.878 --> 1:14:27.755
[Trevor]
Sure. Yeah.

1:14:27.838 --> 1:14:29.674
Ice cream sounds great.

1:14:29.757 --> 1:14:31.384
Come on, Stace.

1:14:32.259 --> 1:14:34.011
Hey, you sure you're okay?

1:14:34.095 --> 1:14:35.012
‐Yep.
‐All right.

1:14:35.096 --> 1:14:37.556
Let's go, guys.

1:14:40.184 --> 1:14:42.895
Look, I'm not sure exactly
what I said, but I think

1:14:42.979 --> 1:14:45.189
maybe it was that you and Eden
were sleeping together.

1:14:45.272 --> 1:14:46.607
‐Oh, Jesus, Helen.
‐I'm sorry.

1:14:46.691 --> 1:14:48.192
[Helen] I‐I really
can't imagine that he

1:14:48.275 --> 1:14:49.860
would do something like this.
I'm really sorry.

1:14:49.944 --> 1:14:52.029
Mom, why are you
apologizing to him?

1:14:52.571 --> 1:14:54.365
Because I fucked up.

1:14:54.448 --> 1:14:55.241
How, exactly?

1:14:55.324 --> 1:14:58.160
Uh, even if Sasha started it,

1:14:58.244 --> 1:14:59.370
does that mean
these women are lying?

1:14:59.453 --> 1:15:01.580
Does that mean
that Dad didn't do

1:15:01.664 --> 1:15:03.541
the things he's
being accused of?

1:15:03.624 --> 1:15:05.918
You believe these women over me?
I'm your father.

1:15:07.545 --> 1:15:09.964
Nobody's saying
that they're lying.

1:15:10.047 --> 1:15:11.841
I'm just saying that maybe
they're exaggerating

1:15:11.924 --> 1:15:13.050
what happened to them.

1:15:13.134 --> 1:15:15.636
‐Why would they do that?
‐For attention.

1:15:15.720 --> 1:15:17.722
I mean, these things happen
on a spectrum, okay?

1:15:17.805 --> 1:15:18.180
Like, what they're describing

1:15:18.264 --> 1:15:20.725
is awkward, yes,

1:15:20.808 --> 1:15:21.225
and uncomfortable, certainly.

1:15:21.308 --> 1:15:23.352
It's not abuse.

1:15:23.436 --> 1:15:25.271
And by calling it abuse,

1:15:25.354 --> 1:15:27.273
you just turn women
into victims.

1:15:27.356 --> 1:15:28.983
And once you get older,

1:15:29.066 --> 1:15:30.985
hopefully you will
understand this.

1:15:31.068 --> 1:15:32.486
Listen to yourself.
Do you hear yourself

1:15:32.570 --> 1:15:33.821
right now when you're talking?

1:15:33.904 --> 1:15:35.740
He cheated on you,
and he left you,

1:15:35.823 --> 1:15:36.449
and he left all of us.

1:15:36.532 --> 1:15:38.993
Why are you still defending him?

1:15:39.076 --> 1:15:41.203
Because he's your father,
and you guys need your father.

1:15:41.287 --> 1:15:42.663
Don't say that.
This isn't about us.

1:15:42.747 --> 1:15:44.040
This has never been about us.

1:15:44.123 --> 1:15:46.625
‐What is it about?
‐You.

1:15:48.919 --> 1:15:50.421
You could never let him go.

1:15:50.504 --> 1:15:52.214
No matter what he did,
you forgave him for it.

1:15:52.298 --> 1:15:54.300
That's not fair.

1:15:56.135 --> 1:15:58.137
And it's not true.
We got a divorce.

1:15:58.220 --> 1:15:59.680
What more did you want from me?

1:15:59.764 --> 1:16:00.514
I wanted you to condemn him.

1:16:00.598 --> 1:16:03.100
I wanted you
to admit to yourself

1:16:03.184 --> 1:16:04.852
and to us what a shit he was,

1:16:04.935 --> 1:16:07.521
so that maybe I would have
an opportunity to acknowledge

1:16:07.605 --> 1:16:09.815
that that behavior
wasn't normal.

1:16:09.899 --> 1:16:12.151
So that maybe I wouldn't
go out looking for a guy

1:16:12.234 --> 1:16:14.153
to hurt me the way
that he hurt you.

1:16:20.451 --> 1:16:23.621
That's what you think of me?

1:16:27.750 --> 1:16:30.336
No, you don't understand.
This is all my fault.

1:16:30.419 --> 1:16:33.047
None of it would have happened.

1:16:33.130 --> 1:16:36.759
I mean, what those women are
saying, that's not... it's not

1:16:36.842 --> 1:16:38.886
who your father is.

1:16:43.349 --> 1:16:45.226
Mom, I believe them.

1:16:45.309 --> 1:16:47.978
<i>♪ tense music ♪</i>

1:16:48.062 --> 1:16:49.105
<i>♪♪♪</i>

1:16:49.188 --> 1:16:51.982
He did it to me.

1:16:52.066 --> 1:16:53.567
‐[Noah] Whitney.
‐What?

1:16:53.651 --> 1:16:54.860
What are you talking about?

1:16:59.240 --> 1:17:02.118
That night at
Rodney Callahan's party.

1:17:02.201 --> 1:17:05.329
When you got in the hot tub,
you didn't recognize me.

1:17:05.412 --> 1:17:08.040
But I saw the way
you look at women.

1:17:12.920 --> 1:17:14.839
Like they're prey.

1:17:14.922 --> 1:17:17.258
What is she talking about?

1:17:18.425 --> 1:17:21.345
What is she talking about?

1:17:25.182 --> 1:17:27.935
‐[Helen] Noah. Noah.
‐[shuddering]

1:17:29.645 --> 1:17:32.565
What is she
talking about?

1:18:01.927 --> 1:18:03.888
<i>♪ atmospheric music ♪</i>

1:18:03.971 --> 1:18:05.848
<i>♪♪♪</i>
